metadata.name: Reconnaissance #73
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they’re recon from another planet’s civilization — one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium “This is Mars,” Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands — and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what’s next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.
Created with p5.js

TENDER x Nat Sarkissian
May 2022

metadata.name: Square Planets #256
metadata.description:
Square Planets was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Planetary Folklore Participations No. 2. (c. 1970). Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the third in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

Square Planets consists of four layers of squares contained within a background square superimposed on top of one another. Each layer is translated from the previous layer but still lies within its boundaries. The background color of each layer is random and its set of squares are another random color. The squares that make up layers two and three are rotated either clockwise or counter-clockwise some random number of degrees within a predetermined range. 

There are many Gestalt interactions within this piece. Layers (square planets) interact with each other in interesting ways. Each new generation with its random color assignments significantly affect your depth perception. Layers appear to come forward or recede. Sometimes there is more "after-imagism" between the square sets. Candy for your mind.

metadata.name: ProcGen Entomology #391
metadata.description:
Realtime 3D in-browser procedural generation of insect-like models, with a look reminiscent of vintage entomology illustrations.

The project is about the fact that insects are cool first and foremost.
This is also about nostalgia.

Everything is procedural except for the font. The exposed features only describe the most visible parts.

I wrote mord words, about where it came from, and some technical details on the procedural aspect at:
https://ulucode.com/projects/entomology/

GPU Required!

metadata.name: Antiflow #106
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.

metadata.name: The Modern Prometheus #71
metadata.description:
We are collections of the various people we've met. Each one of us is different but also is different to everyone we meet. We construct ourselves out of others' identities, traumas, shared experiences, and stories we tell ourselves (and have told about us). 

Like the resurrected monster, we live and learn through the way others react to us. We each yearn to be loved, and lash out against things trying to harm us. Without empathy, we're all the protagonists of our own story, and the monster is someone else's.

Like Dr. Victor Frankenstein, we experiment and bring life to things that we can't fully comprehend. We also cannot understand the full extent of the unintended consequences of our actions.

Whether NFTs will be a net positive or negative to society is far from decided, and, like these creatures you're minting, you may find beauty or horror when all is said and done.

metadata.name: stigmergy #136
metadata.description:
Stigmergy is a method of decentralized organization in which agents communicate by leaving traces in a shared environment. This piece simulates a kind of stigmergy among a large population of particles. Each particle leaves a trail behind it as it moves, and determines its direction of motion based on the trails around it. The rules for how a particle should move based on its surroundings were created with a user-guided evolutionary process.

Press "c" to capture a 2048x2048 image of the simulation. You can also press the spacebar to pause/unpause the simulation, and press "n" while paused to move the simulation forward a single step.

metadata.name: Scythe of Atropos #24
metadata.description:
Scythe of Atropos: A Moiraic sister piece to ‘Filigree of Lachesis’ and ‘Braiding of Clotho’.

“‘Tis true. There's magic in the web of it.”

A random walker emerges from the central void, disgorging ellipse and rectangle with the certainty of Perlin noise. Hue plays a greater part in this piece, and whitespace forms beneath the delicate tracework of thin black lines. A dance of rectangles swirl around the central point, interspersed with elliptical forms.

Rendering is complete after a certain number of frames, at which point a high-resolution png can be exported by pressing 's'.

Features vary in rarity, and affect weighting, size, colour and density of stroke.

Entropy is high.

metadata.name: Fire Card #9
metadata.description:
Fire Cards is a series of generative artworks inspired by 19th-century Japanese fireworks catalogues. The images in these catalogues didn't so much focus on realism, but on the visual associations of the pyrotechnic effects instead. Using a restricted color palette and relatively simple shapes, this resulted in vibrant, graphical posters that sparked your own imagination more than anything else.

In Fire Cards, the abstract, static images are transformed back into lively, dynamic worlds again, each with their own distinctive, centuries-old aesthetics. Using a custom animation and 2D render system, the algorithmically generated worlds slowly build up and show a magical fireworks performance.

Fire Cards are tiny, personal and unique shows of wonder.
